                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=darby",
                        "name": "darby",
                        "displayName": "Darby Felton",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Minor update to summary and affects version 0.9.2.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=darby",
                        "name": "darby",
                        "displayName": "Darby Felton",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-04-12T16:29:23.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-04-12T16:29:23.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/14880",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rob",
                        "name": "rob",
                        "displayName": "Rob Allen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "As ArrayAccess implementation doesn't allow the object to be used with the array_XXX() functions, I think that there is very little benefit in adding this functionality to Zend_Config. \n\nIf you need an array, then Zend_Config::toArray() will generate one for you.\n\nHave I missed a use-case where ArrayAccess makes something possible or much easier than the current access functionality?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rob",
                        "name": "rob",
                        "displayName": "Rob Allen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-05-30T16:13:05.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-05-30T16:13:05.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/14884",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bate",
                        "name": "bate",
                        "displayName": "Marco Kaiser",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "The reason is very easy, because if you use other templating system (ie. smarty) its not possible to make things like\n$config->value->subvalue\n\n$config.value.subvalue is possible this the one reason the other reason is, you can extend the class with more features and logic.\nOtherwise change the constructor from Zend_Config calls to self:: calls because it makesit very hard to build around this class with such an nested forced type.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bate",
                        "name": "bate",
                        "displayName": "Marco Kaiser",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-05-31T03:12:58.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-05-31T03:12:58.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/14885",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rob",
                        "name": "rob",
                        "displayName": "Rob Allen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "We use {$obj->property} with no problems within Smarty with our ZF application. What error message are you getting?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rob",
                        "name": "rob",
                        "displayName": "Rob Allen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-05-31T03:46:35.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-05-31T03:46:35.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/14888",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bate",
                        "name": "bate",
                        "displayName": "Marco Kaiser",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "[system]\napplication.name = \"TestApplication\"\napplication.version.major = 1\napplication.version.minor = 0\napplication.version.revision = 156\n\n\nthis is a config application example\n\nthis results in an object\nthat looks like this:\n\nZend_Config Object\n(\n    [_data:protected] => Array\n    (\n        [application] => Zend_Config Object\n        (\n            [_data:protected] => Array\n            (\n                [name] => TestApplication\n                [version] => Zend_Config Object\n                (\n                    [_data:protected] => Array\n                    (\n                        [major] => 1\n                        [minor] => 0\n                        [revision] => 156\n                    )\n                )\n            )\n        )\n    )\n)\n\n\nto access this in a smarty template you can just use\n$config.version.major and not\n$config->version->major\n\nthe way to build a own abstraction is easy like\nclass my_config extends Zend_Config implements ArrayAccess\n{\n  public function offsetExists($offset)\n  public function offsetGet($offset)\n  public function offsetSet($offset, $value)\n  public function offsetUnset($offset)\n}\n\nbut the parent constructor from Zend_Config does stuff like\n$this->_data[$key] = new Zend_Config($value, $this->_allowModifications);\n\nthis makes it impossible to get a deep recursion with my own abstraction. The way to overload the constructor are\npossible but is not the clean way. It would be better to change the constructor and implement the arrayaccess feature to\nadd own functionality like a config object with methods and array access.\n\n{if $config->hasVersion()}\n{$config->version->id}\n{\/if}\n\njust one example ... :)",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bate",
                        "name": "bate",
                        "displayName": "Marco Kaiser",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-05-31T04:28:17.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-05-31T04:28:17.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
    },
